NIEUWE ONTVANGER

Willem Bos besprak laatst een nieuwe wereld
ontvanger, de Lowe HF-125, in onze uitzending.
Er kwamen vragen om eem meer gedetailleerd
rapport. We worden op onze wenken bediend
door Jonathan Marks van Radio Netherlands
(Wereldomroep) die een gedetailleerd verslag
in het Engels op papier zette.

A new shortwave communications
receiver's just come onto the European
market made by Lowe electronics in
Derbyshire England. It's lightweight at
1.8 kilos in its standard version, and
being 25 by 10 by 20 centimetres in
size, it's also very compact. It comes
with a 12 volt DC power adaptor for use
on 220 volts AC current in Europe.
Although this is an external unit, the
fact that the transformer is outside
the radio doesn't lead to hum problems
as experienced with other radios that
have tried this in the past.

The beginner will have no problems
connecting up an antenna, a pair of
headphones or a tape-recorder. Lowe
electronics have written a clear,
logical instruction manual plus a
booklet that explains what to listen
out for when you start tuning around.
Part of its attraction is the
simplicity. There are just 9 controls
on the front panel, which can be tilted
up to face the operator. Up to 30
frequencies can be stored in the
radio's memory. A large clear back-lit
liquid crystal display shows the
frequency being received to the near 1
kilohertz.

MANUAL TUNING

To the right is a manual rotary tuning
knob, and if you turn that slowly
you'll move up and down the band in 60
Hz steps which are inaudible. Turning
the knob faster switches the unit to
steps of 250 Hz in the AM mode, that's
the listening mode you'd use to listen
to broadcast stations. If you select
either upper or lower sideband or
the CW mode as you'd do for radio
amateurs or telex stations, the slowest
tuning step drops to 15.6 Hz. Since the
receiver is extremely stable, the fine
tuning steps allows you to accurately
tune in a radio-teletype station with
ease. The receiver also has a
narrow-band FM option for monitoring
citizen's band on 27 MHz for instance,
but we didn't test this mode ourselves.

SELECTIVITY

The HF-125 offers 4 different
selectivity positions, and the filters
are quite reasonable. There's a very
wide 10 kHz setting, best suited when
your listening to local medium wave
stations, and then the low distortion
audio sounds very pleasant indeed to
European ears. The 7 kHz setting is
best suited to shortwave when you've
found a strong clear signal. The 4 KHz
option is more useful when the signal
you're listening to is suffering from
strong stations operating on
frequencies 5 kHz either side of the
one you're trying to monitor. And
finally, if you're trying to dig
something out of the noise, or looking
for utility stations, the 2.5 kHz
filter is the best suited. Quite a
choice on a receiver of this price
class.

SENSITIVITY

The sensitivity of a receiver is less
important these days. Shortwave
stations using hundreds of kilowatts
are able to deliver quite a strong
signal into many target areas,
especially Europe and parts of Asia.
The HF-125 is very sensitive, signals
of just half a microvolt being usable
in the narrowest AM mode. The
receiver's built-in
synthesizer generates a lot of noise
between 30 and 70 kilohertz, thats way
down in the very low frequency part of
the spectrum. This masks most of the
signals coming in. But from 100 kHz up
to 30,000 kHz, covered continuously on
this set with no breaks, the
sensitivity is remarkably uniform. The
receiver offers an analogue signal
strength meter which turns out to be
very accurately calibrated, far more
than just a tuning gimmick.

BIRDIES - 10 MAJOR ONES

If you put a shortwave receiver inside
a metal cage so that its screened off
from the outside world, you can then
measure ghost signals on the dial which
are generated by the set itself. They
appear as a silent carrier if your
listening on AM or a whistle if you're
listening on single-sideband. Most sets
of this price range suffer from these
so-called birdies, and you can't get
rid of all of them without drastically
increasing the price of the radio...the
designers aim is to make them as weak
as possible and on frequencies that are
outside major broadcast and amateur
bands. We measured more than 40 low
level birdies on the HF-125. Most of
these disappear below the noise level
when you connect an antenna, but we
found 10 'birdies' which were above 1
microvolt, and therefore noticable. A
few fall in broadcast and amateur radio
bands. There's one on exactly 6 and 12
MHz for instance, but also on 1500,
4901, 9891, 11954, 14082, 14164 and
14240 kHz. If you try and tune in a
station on these channels, you get
extra distortion or interference
generated by the HF-125 itself. More
expensive sets like the Yaesu FRG-8800
and ICOM ICR-71 have birdies too, but
not quite as many.

FAIR DYNAMIC RANGE

The most serious drawback of the HF-125
is its dynamic range. While it's better
than most portables, its only fair by
communication receiver standards. Since
the front end of the receiver is wide
open for signals on quite a wide range
of frequencies, if you're trying to
listen to a weak signal on the 49 metre
band, and a powerhouse signal opens up
about 200 kHz further down the dial,
the receiver becomes desensitized as it
were, and reception of the weak signal
suffers. You can reduce the problem
somewhat by using a sharp aerial
preselector, but we were unable to
separate a weak signal on 6085 kHz from
a powerhouse on nearby 6090 kHz, even
with the narrowest filter selected.
This problem will be less outside
Europe, where signal strengths on the
band tend to be lower.

NO ACTIVE ANTENNAS

The Lowe instruction book warns against
connecting huge antennas. We found an
active antenna such as the Datong
AD-270 or Dressler ARA 30 was totally
unsuitable with the HF-125 in Europe.
Even with the 20 dB internal attenuator
switched on, the active antennas were
delivering more signal than the radio
can handle. The short long wire or
dipole recommended in the instruction
book gave much better results. In
practice we found the medium wave
performance to be good. Over the last 4
weeks we tested the HF-125 with a
medium wave loop, and were able to log
North American East Coast stations
during good conditions.

PRICE

The HF-125 costs 375 pounds including
Value added Tax in Britain. For an
extra 59 pounds 50 you can plug in a
keyboard, and then enter frequencies
directly into the set. The software
here is friendly, simple and logical.
For another 59 pounds 50, you can also
have a FM board installed, plus a
synchronous AM detector. This mode
generally offers better audio fidelity
on shortwave signals, especially during
deep fades. Our experience was that
although the synchronous detection
system does work, it doesn't lock onto
very weak signals, and when this mode
is used, the audio sounds less
pleasant. That's very subjective
though. You can also have a rechargable
battery supply, plus active whip
antenna installed, but we didn't test
this optional extra, which is another
69 pounds 50.

It's refreshing to find a receiver that
does exactly what it claims. The
manufacturers specifications check out
perfectly, and Lowe electronics have
acheived all the aims they've set
themselves. The HF-125 will be of
interest to the serious shortwave
listener and beginning DXer looking for
a no-frills receiver which sounds nice,
and can handle a wide range of signal
types. The fair dynamic range is main
limiting factor, but you can't expect
much more for the price being asked
for. The set is currently being
distributed in Europe, and there are
plans to introduce it on the North
American market shortly.
